## Summary Table of Key Factors

| Factor                      | Description                                                                                 | Impact on Protests                           |
|-----------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------|
| Economic Crisis             | GDP contraction, inflation (500%-900%), shortages of food, medicine, fuel                   | Primary driver of public frustration          |
| U.S. Sanctions             | Embargo intensified under Trump, restrictions on remittances, trade, and finance           | Exacerbated economic hardships                |
| COVID-19 Pandemic          | Health system overwhelmed, resurgence of cases, halted tourism                             | Deepened economic and social crisis           |
| Political Repression       | Lack of freedoms, arrests, propaganda, internet blackouts                                  | Fuelled political dissent and calls for change|
| Generational Shift         | Younger Cubans disillusioned with regime, loss of revolutionary legitimacy                 | Reduced regime support                         |
| Social Media & Culture     | Internet access, viral protest songs, online mobilization                                 | Enabled rapid spread and coordination of protests |

---

## Conclusion and Opinion

The Cuban protests of July 2021 were the result of a perfect storm of economic collapse, public health crisis, and political repression. While U.S. sanctions have undeniably worsened Cuba’s economic situation by restricting access to foreign currency and trade, internal factors such as a rigid centrally planned economy, delayed reforms, and mismanagement have also played critical roles.

The COVID-19 pandemic acted as a catalyst, exposing and deepening existing vulnerabilities. The government's failure to adequately address food and medicine shortages, combined with rising inflation and power outages, directly impacted daily life and livelihoods, pushing citizens to the breaking point.

Politically, the protests reveal a significant erosion of the regime's legitimacy, especially among younger Cubans who have grown up without the revolutionary fervor that sustained earlier generations. The role of social media in organizing and amplifying dissent marks a new dynamic in Cuban society.

In my assessment, addressing Cuba's crisis requires a multifaceted approach: easing sanctions to allow humanitarian aid and remittances, coupled with genuine economic reforms and political openness from the Cuban government. Without such changes, the underlying grievances that sparked the protests will persist, risking further instability.

